<paragraph id="8BF69A3CFFC44A39D6AAC306FB4BF8E4" blockId="8.[981,1247,1799,1820]" box="[981,1247,1799,1820]" pageId="8" pageNumber="177">
<heading id="D0BE2D50FFC44A39D6AAC306FB4BF8E4" box="[981,1247,1799,1820]" centered="true" fontSize="8" level="2" pageId="8" pageNumber="177" reason="8">
<taxonomicName id="4C49E1BFFFC44A39D6AAC306FBC5F8E5" authorityName="Girard" authorityYear="1857" box="[981,1105,1799,1820]" class="Reptilia" family="Tropiduridae" genus="Eulaemus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="8" pageNumber="177" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93D462EFFC44A39D6AAC306FBC5F8E5" box="[981,1105,1799,1820]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="177">EULAEMUS</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
PHYLOGENY
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF69A3CFFC44A38D659C33AFB0FF9C2" blockId="8.[806,1421,1850,1903]" lastBlockId="9.[826,1441,1483,1903]" lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="178" pageId="8" pageNumber="177">
Here we used four different methods representing different conceptual approaches to reconstruct phylogenies of the subgenus 
<taxonomicName id="4C49E1BFFFC54A38D41DC1CAFE40FA1F" authorityName="Girard" authorityYear="1857" box="[354,468,1483,1504]" class="Reptilia" family="Tropiduridae" genus="Eulaemus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="9" pageNumber="178" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93D462EFFC54A38D41DC1CAFE40FA1F" box="[354,468,1483,1504]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="178">Eulaemus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. First, we used a complete matrix of 188 terminals and 14 loci (MDC and concatenated analyses), and then selected representatives of the main clades for which we implemented two Bayesian species tree methods (*BEAST and BEST). All of our analyses strongly support the 
<taxonomicName id="4C49E1BFFFC54A38D5DBC283FEC8F968" box="[164,348,1666,1687]" class="Reptilia" family="Liolaemidae" genus="Liolaemus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="9" pageNumber="178" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="lineomaculatus">
<emphasis id="B93D462EFFC54A38D5DBC283FEC8F968" box="[164,348,1666,1687]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="178">lineomaculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
section as the sister clade of the 
<taxonomicName id="4C49E1BFFFC54A38D5DBC2A3FE80F948" box="[164,276,1698,1719]" class="Reptilia" family="Liolaemidae" genus="Liolaemus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="9" pageNumber="178" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="montanus">
<emphasis id="B93D462EFFC54A38D5DBC2A3FE80F948" box="[164,276,1698,1719]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="178">montanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
section (
<figureCitation id="137286B9FFC54A38D404C2A0FE2EF948" box="[379,442,1697,1719]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="7.[164,243,1526,1545]" captionTargetBox="[164,1445,194,1496]" captionTargetId="figure-0@7.[164,1445,194,1496]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figure 3. Empirical Eulaemus phylogenetic hypotheses. Phylogenetic results using the full matrix of 188 taxa (A, B) and a reduced set of 40 taxa chosen to subsample the largest clades (C to F). A, topology recovered from the concatenated matrix; B, species tree recovered by the minimizing deep coalescence (MDC) approach; C, *BEAST results of partial matrix with representatives of largest clades; values on branches are estimated divergences times (upper) and posterior probability values estimated (lower) or separated by a slash; bold branches represent nodal support&gt; 0.90; D, BEST result; E, MDC result of partial matrix; and F, partial concatenated matrix. In (A), (D), and (F) nodes with support &lt;0.90 were collapsed. The calibration point for estimation of divergence times is shown with a white circle in the node corresponding to the divergence of the Eulaemus and Liolaemus clades." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5337488" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5337488/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="178">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
A-F). We also recovered identical main clades within the 
<taxonomicName id="4C49E1BFFFC54A38D498C2C1FDC2F92A" box="[487,598,1728,1749]" class="Reptilia" family="Liolaemidae" genus="Liolaemus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="9" pageNumber="178" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="montanus">
<emphasis id="B93D462EFFC54A38D498C2C1FDC2F92A" box="[487,598,1728,1749]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="178">montanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
section with all four methods, with the exception of the paraphyletic 
<taxonomicName id="4C49E1BFFFC54A38D5DBC2FCFE99F8ED" box="[164,269,1789,1810]" class="Reptilia" family="Liolaemidae" genus="Liolaemus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="9" pageNumber="178" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="melanops">
<emphasis id="B93D462EFFC54A38D5DBC2FCFE99F8ED" box="[164,269,1789,1810]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="178">melanops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
series’ groups in the MDC analysis (
<figureCitation id="137286B9FFC54A38D7D3C2FCFD69F8EC" box="[684,765,1789,1811]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="7.[164,243,1526,1545]" captionTargetBox="[164,1445,194,1496]" captionTargetId="figure-0@7.[164,1445,194,1496]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figure 3. Empirical Eulaemus phylogenetic hypotheses. Phylogenetic results using the full matrix of 188 taxa (A, B) and a reduced set of 40 taxa chosen to subsample the largest clades (C to F). A, topology recovered from the concatenated matrix; B, species tree recovered by the minimizing deep coalescence (MDC) approach; C, *BEAST results of partial matrix with representatives of largest clades; values on branches are estimated divergences times (upper) and posterior probability values estimated (lower) or separated by a slash; bold branches represent nodal support&gt; 0.90; D, BEST result; E, MDC result of partial matrix; and F, partial concatenated matrix. In (A), (D), and (F) nodes with support &lt;0.90 were collapsed. The calibration point for estimation of divergence times is shown with a white circle in the node corresponding to the divergence of the Eulaemus and Liolaemus clades." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5337488" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5337488/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="178">Fig. 3E</figureCitation>
), but these were recovered as monophyletic in the MDC and the concatenated analysis for the full matrix (
<figureCitation id="137286B9FFC54A38D5D3C358FEB1F891" box="[172,293,1881,1903]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="7.[164,243,1526,1545]" captionTargetBox="[164,1445,194,1496]" captionTargetId="figure-0@7.[164,1445,194,1496]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figure 3. Empirical Eulaemus phylogenetic hypotheses. Phylogenetic results using the full matrix of 188 taxa (A, B) and a reduced set of 40 taxa chosen to subsample the largest clades (C to F). A, topology recovered from the concatenated matrix; B, species tree recovered by the minimizing deep coalescence (MDC) approach; C, *BEAST results of partial matrix with representatives of largest clades; values on branches are estimated divergences times (upper) and posterior probability values estimated (lower) or separated by a slash; bold branches represent nodal support&gt; 0.90; D, BEST result; E, MDC result of partial matrix; and F, partial concatenated matrix. In (A), (D), and (F) nodes with support &lt;0.90 were collapsed. The calibration point for estimation of divergence times is shown with a white circle in the node corresponding to the divergence of the Eulaemus and Liolaemus clades." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5337488" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5337488/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="178">Fig. 3A, B</figureCitation>
). However, we did not fully resolve rela- tionships amongst these main clades owing to short, weakly supported internodes, and the same was true for relationships amongst the main clades within the 
<taxonomicName id="4C49E1BFFFC54A38D645C226FC3FF9C3" box="[826,939,1575,1596]" class="Reptilia" family="Liolaemidae" genus="Liolaemus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="9" pageNumber="178" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="montanus">
<emphasis id="B93D462EFFC54A38D645C226FC3FF9C3" box="[826,939,1575,1596]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="178">montanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
section (
<figureCitation id="137286B9FFC54A38D169C226FB1AF9C2" box="[1046,1166,1575,1597]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="7.[164,243,1526,1545]" captionTargetBox="[164,1445,194,1496]" captionTargetId="figure-0@7.[164,1445,194,1496]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figure 3. Empirical Eulaemus phylogenetic hypotheses. Phylogenetic results using the full matrix of 188 taxa (A, B) and a reduced set of 40 taxa chosen to subsample the largest clades (C to F). A, topology recovered from the concatenated matrix; B, species tree recovered by the minimizing deep coalescence (MDC) approach; C, *BEAST results of partial matrix with representatives of largest clades; values on branches are estimated divergences times (upper) and posterior probability values estimated (lower) or separated by a slash; bold branches represent nodal support&gt; 0.90; D, BEST result; E, MDC result of partial matrix; and F, partial concatenated matrix. In (A), (D), and (F) nodes with support &lt;0.90 were collapsed. The calibration point for estimation of divergence times is shown with a white circle in the node corresponding to the divergence of the Eulaemus and Liolaemus clades." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5337488" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5337488/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="178">Fig. 3A, C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption id="DF36CAB4FFC54A38D5DBC0FDFB6AFA7B" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5337490" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5337490" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5337490/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="178" startId="9.[164,243,1276,1295]" targetBox="[389,1218,198,1242]" targetPageId="9">
<paragraph id="8BF69A3CFFC54A38D5DBC0FDFB6AFA7B" blockId="9.[164,1442,1276,1412]" pageId="9" pageNumber="178">
<emphasis id="B93D462EFFC54A38D5DBC0FDFE98FAF0" bold="true" box="[164,268,1276,1295]" pageId="9" pageNumber="178">Figure 4.</emphasis>
Simulation results. Total number of loci supporting each model after comparisons of the data against 1000 simulated data sets for each locus for each model, and compared with data. We compared the 1000 simulated trees against the model and obtained an approximation of a probability distribution of the deep coalescences expected, and then compared the number of deep coalescences on the observed tree (real data) against the probability distribution. Here, we the show number of loci that fell within the 95% confidence intervals of those probability distributions.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<subSubSection id="C353C9B7FFC54A3AD62CC244FE60FF04" lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="180" pageId="9" pageNumber="178" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BF69A3CFFC54A3BD62CC244FEF8FE2E" blockId="9.[826,1441,1483,1903]" lastBlockId="10.[144,759,198,1902]" lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="179" pageId="9" pageNumber="178">
Previously published phylogenetic studies of the genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C49E1BFFFC54A38D645C265FC38F986" box="[826,940,1636,1657]" class="Reptilia" family="Liolaemidae" genus="Liolaemus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="9" pageNumber="178" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93D462EFFC54A38D645C265FC38F986" box="[826,940,1636,1657]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="178">Liolaemus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
show extensive topological incongruence (e.g. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFD8E7CDFFC54A38D645C283FC67F967" author="Etheridge R" box="[826,1011,1666,1688]" pageId="9" pageNumber="178" pagination="1 - 34" refId="ref10384" refString="Etheridge R. 1995. Redescription of Ctenoblepharys adspersa (Tschudi, 1845), and the taxonomy of Liolaeminae (Reptilia: Squamata: Tropiduridae). American Museum Novitates 3142: 1 - 34." type="journal article" year="1995">Etheridge, 1995</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFD8E7CDFFC54A38D17EC282FBAEF967" author="Etheridge R" box="[1025,1082,1667,1688]" pageId="9" pageNumber="178" pagination="293 - 352" refId="ref10421" refString="Etheridge R. 2000. A review of lizards of the Liolaemus wiegmannii Group (Squamata, Iguania, Tropiduridae). And a history of morphological change in the sand-dwelling species. Herpetological Monographs 14: 293 - 352." type="journal article" year="2000">2000</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFD8E7CDFFC54A38D138C283FAB1F967" author="Schulte JA II &amp; Macey JR &amp; Espinoza RE &amp; Larson A" box="[1095,1317,1666,1688]" pageId="9" pageNumber="178" pagination="75 - 102" refId="ref11644" refString="Schulte JA II, Macey JR, Espinoza RE, Larson A. 2000. Phylogenetic relationships in the iguanid lizard genus Liolaemus: multiple origins of viviparous reproduction and evidence for recurring Andean vicariance and dispersal. Biological Journal of the Linnean Society 69: 75 - 102." type="journal article" year="2000">
Schulte 
<emphasis id="B93D462EFFC54A38D1DAC282FB42F968" box="[1189,1238,1666,1688]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="178">et al</emphasis>
., 2000
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFD8E7CDFFC54A38D04DC283FBBDF949" author="Espinoza RE &amp; Wiens JJ &amp; Tracy CR" pageId="9" pageNumber="178" pagination="16819 - 16824" refId="ref10305" refString="Espinoza RE, Wiens JJ, Tracy CR. 2004. Recurrent evolution of herbivory in small, cold-climate lizards: breaking the ecophysiological rules of reptilian herbivory. Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, USA 101: 16819 - 16824." type="journal article" year="2004">Espinoza, Wiens &amp; Tracy, 2004</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFD8E7CDFFC54A38D149C2A0FB63F948" author="Avila LJ &amp; Morando M &amp; Sites JW Jr." box="[1078,1271,1697,1719]" pageId="9" pageNumber="178" pagination="241 - 275" refId="ref9720" refString="Avila LJ, Morando M, Sites JW Jr. 2006. Congeneric phylogeography: hypothesizing species limits and evolutionary processes in Patagonian lizards of the Liolaemus boulengeri group (Squamata: Liolaemini). Biological Journal of the Linnean Society 89: 241 - 275." type="journal article" year="2006">
Avila 
<emphasis id="B93D462EFFC54A38D107C2A3FB3CF949" box="[1144,1192,1697,1719]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="178">et al</emphasis>
., 2006
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFD8E7CDFFC54A38D07BC2A0FA09F949" author="Abdala CS" box="[1284,1437,1697,1719]" pageId="9" pageNumber="178" pagination="1 - 84" refId="ref9574" refString="Abdala CS. 2007. Phylogeny of the boulengeri group (Iguania: Liolaemidae, Liolaemus). Zootaxa 1538: 1 - 84." type="journal article" year="2007">Abdala, 2007</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFD8E7CDFFC54A38D645C2C1FBC6F929" author="Fontanella FM &amp; Olave M &amp; Avila LJ &amp; Sites JW Jr &amp; Morando M" box="[826,1106,1728,1750]" pageId="9" pageNumber="178" pagination="825 - 835" refId="ref10509" refString="Fontanella FM, Olave M, Avila LJ, Sites JW Jr, Morando M. 2012. Molecular dating and diversification of the South American lizard genus Liolaemus (subgenus Eulaemus) based on nuclear and mitochondrial DNA sequences. Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society 164: 825 - 835." type="journal article" year="2012">
Fontanella 
<emphasis id="B93D462EFFC54A38D6B8C2C1FC6FF92A" box="[967,1019,1728,1749]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="178">et al</emphasis>
., 2012
</bibRefCitation>
), with few shared strongly supported hypotheses; thus, no consensus has been reached. In this most inclusive study to date, we did not recover a strongly supported and fully resolved phylogeny, and we represent the uncertain relationships as polytomies. Although these polytomies may be re- solved by adding more data, they may also indicate rapid radiations amongst some clades. However, before arriving at this conclusion, we need to consider that poor branch support can also be the result of: (1) insufficiently informative data; (2) data sets that strongly conflict with one another; (3) inappropriate phylogenetic methods and substitution models; or (4) insufficient data to resolve short branches (
<bibRefCitation id="EFD8E7CDFFC64A3BD7F3C59DFEF5FE2E" author="Whitfield JB &amp; Lockhart PJ" pageId="10" pageNumber="179" pagination="258 - 265" refId="ref12162" refString="Whitfield JB, Lockhart PJ. 2007. Deciphering ancient rapid radiations. Trends in Ecology &amp; Evolution 22: 258 - 265." type="journal article" year="2007">Whitfield &amp; Lockhart, 2007</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF69A3CFFC64A3BD5D7C5DBFEFDFA3D" blockId="10.[144,759,198,1902]" pageId="10" pageNumber="179">
To address point 1, we explored the informativeness of our data set using likelihood-mapping as well as saturation tests and phylogenetic signal index calculations. These analyses showed that all of the 13 loci included in our empirical analyses and simulations are phylogenetically informative, and although it was not possible to resolve the relationships amongst the main clades within the 
<taxonomicName id="4C49E1BFFFC64A3BD41DC6B1FE47FD3A" box="[354,467,688,709]" class="Reptilia" family="Liolaemidae" genus="Liolaemus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="10" pageNumber="179" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="montanus">
<emphasis id="B93D462EFFC64A3BD41DC6B1FE47FD3A" box="[354,467,688,709]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="179">montanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
section, our data are informative enough to resolve the oldest divergence (between the 
<taxonomicName id="4C49E1BFFFC64A3BD440C6ECFE23FCFD" box="[319,439,749,770]" class="Reptilia" family="Liolaemidae" genus="Liolaemus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="10" pageNumber="179" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="montanus">
<emphasis id="B93D462EFFC64A3BD440C6ECFE23FCFD" box="[319,439,749,770]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="179">montanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C49E1BFFFC64A3BD77FC6EDFD2FFCFE" box="[512,699,748,769]" class="Reptilia" family="Liolaemidae" genus="Liolaemus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="10" pageNumber="179" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="lineomaculatus">
<emphasis id="B93D462EFFC64A3BD77FC6EDFD2FFCFE" box="[512,699,748,769]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="179">lineomaculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sections), as well as providing high levels of resolution within each main clade (results not shown; see 
<bibRefCitation id="EFD8E7CDFFC64A3BD7CBC72BFE87FCA1" author="Olave M &amp; Avila LJ &amp; Sites JW &amp; Morando M" pageId="10" pageNumber="179" pagination="323 - 337" refId="ref11418" refString="Olave M, Avila LJ, Sites JW, Jr, Morando M. 2014. Multilocus phylogeny of the widely distributed South American lizard clade Eulaemus (Liolaemini, Liolaemus). Zoologica Scripta 43: 323 - 337." type="journal article" year="2014">
Olave 
<emphasis id="B93D462EFFC64A3BD5EFC748FF54FCA2" box="[144,192,840,862]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="179">et al</emphasis>
., 2014
</bibRefCitation>
). This suggests that our data set is sufficiently informative to resolve recent and ancient divergences, probably because we included loci with relatively high (12S and cyt-b), intermediate (KIF24, A12D, A1D, A4B, A9C), and low substitution rates (EXPH5, PRLR, SNCAIP, CMOS, DNAH3, MXRA5, PNN; see details in 
<tableCitation id="C6CBAF87FFC64A3BD400C001FE41FBE9" box="[383,469,1024,1046]" captionStart="Table 2" captionStartId="8.[806,869,198,217]" captionText="Table 2. Mutation rates estimates for each locus in site per million years (s/Myr). Right column shows mean, followed by the SD, and below the highest probability density (HPD) of 95%" pageId="10" pageNumber="179">Table 2</tableCitation>
). In our experience with other lizard clades, some combination of these or similar loci is usually sufficient to recover well-resolved/wellsupported trees (
<bibRefCitation id="EFD8E7CDFFC64A3BD42FC05DFDD8FB8E" author="Benavides E &amp; Baum R &amp; Snell HM &amp; Snell HL &amp; Sites JW Jr." box="[336,588,1116,1138]" pageId="10" pageNumber="179" pagination="1606 - 1626" refId="ref9861" refString="Benavides E, Baum R, Snell HM, Snell HL, Sites JW Jr. 2009. Island biogeography of Galapagos lava lizards (Tropiduridae: Microlophus): species diversity, arrival times, and colonization within the archipelago. Evolution 63: 1606 - 1626." type="journal article" year="2009">
Benavides 
<emphasis id="B93D462EFFC64A3BD4B1C05DFE6AFB8E" box="[462,510,1116,1137]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="179">et al</emphasis>
., 2009
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFD8E7CDFFC64A3BD727C05DFF5FFB70" author="Sinclair EA &amp; Pramuk PB &amp; Bezy RL &amp; Crandall KA &amp; Sites JW Jr." pageId="10" pageNumber="179" pagination="1346 - 1357" refId="ref11694" refString="Sinclair EA, Pramuk PB, Bezy RL, Crandall KA, Sites JW Jr. 2010. DNA evidence for nonhybrid origins of parthenogenesis in natural populations of vertebrates. Evolution 64: 1346 - 1357." type="journal article" year="2010">
Sinclair 
<emphasis id="B93D462EFFC64A3BD7C6C05DFD7DFB8E" box="[697,745,1116,1137]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="179">et al</emphasis>
., 2010
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFD8E7CDFFC64A3BD5A3C07BFE75FB70" author="Breitman MF &amp; Avila LJ &amp; Sites JW Jr &amp; Morando M" box="[220,481,1146,1168]" pageId="10" pageNumber="179" pagination="364 - 376" refId="ref9910" refString="Breitman MF, Avila LJ, Sites JW Jr, Morando M. 2011. Lizards from the end of the world: phylogenetic relationships of the Liolaemus lineomaculatus section (Squamata: Iguania: Liolaemini). Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution 59: 364 - 376." type="journal article" year="2011">
Breitman 
<emphasis id="B93D462EFFC64A3BD426C07AFE18FB70" box="[345,396,1146,1168]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="179">et al</emphasis>
., 2011
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFD8E7CDFFC64A3BD48DC07BFD66FB70" author="Camargo A &amp; Avila LJ &amp; Morando M &amp; Sites JW Jr." box="[498,754,1146,1168]" pageId="10" pageNumber="179" pagination="272 - 288" refId="ref10058" refString="Camargo A, Avila LJ, Morando M, Sites JW Jr. 2012. Accuracy and precision of species trees: effects of locus, individual and base pair sampling on inference of species trees in lizards of the Liolaemus darwinii Group (Squamata, Liolaemidae). Systematic Biology 61: 272 - 288." type="journal article" year="2012">
Camargo 
<emphasis id="B93D462EFFC64A3BD716C07AFD08FB70" box="[617,668,1146,1168]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="179">et al</emphasis>
., 2012
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFD8E7CDFFC64A3BD5EFC098FEEBFB50" author="Werneck FP &amp; Gamble T &amp; Colli GR &amp; Rodrigues MT &amp; Sites JW Jr." box="[144,383,1177,1199]" pageId="10" pageNumber="179" pagination="3014 - 3034" refId="ref12115" refString="Werneck FP, Gamble T, Colli GR, Rodrigues MT, Sites JW Jr. 2012. Deep diversification and long-term persistence in the South American ' dry diagonal': integrating continent-wide phylogeography and distribution modeling of geckos. Evolution 66: 3014 - 3034." type="journal article" year="2012">
Werneck 
<emphasis id="B93D462EFFC64A3BD583C098FEB9FB51" box="[252,301,1177,1198]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="179">et al</emphasis>
., 2012
</bibRefCitation>
). Further, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFD8E7CDFFC64A3BD482C098FD62FB50" author="Camargo A &amp; Avila LJ &amp; Morando M &amp; Sites JW Jr." box="[509,758,1177,1199]" pageId="10" pageNumber="179" pagination="272 - 288" refId="ref10058" refString="Camargo A, Avila LJ, Morando M, Sites JW Jr. 2012. Accuracy and precision of species trees: effects of locus, individual and base pair sampling on inference of species trees in lizards of the Liolaemus darwinii Group (Squamata, Liolaemidae). Systematic Biology 61: 272 - 288." type="journal article" year="2012">
Camargo 
<emphasis id="B93D462EFFC64A3BD711C098FD0AFB51" box="[622,670,1177,1198]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="179">et al</emphasis>
. (2012)
</bibRefCitation>
showed in simulation studies that the accuracy of Bayesian species tree methods is significantly higher when multiple loci of different mutation rates are used. Multiple samples per species are also necessary for successful estimation of species trees in *BEAST and although we had to reduce the number of samples per species, simulation studies show that even two samples per species are sufficient given enough loci (
<bibRefCitation id="EFD8E7CDFFC64A3BD7EAC18FFECAFA3D" author="Heled J &amp; Drummond AJ" pageId="10" pageNumber="179" pagination="570 - 580" refId="ref10611" refString="Heled J, Drummond AJ. 2010. Bayesian inference of species trees from Multilocus data. Molecular Biology and Evolution 27: 570 - 580." type="journal article" year="2010">Heled &amp; Drummond, 2010</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF69A3CFFC64A3BD5D7C1CAFF4EF92A" blockId="10.[144,759,198,1902]" pageId="10" pageNumber="179">To minimize the effects of points 2 (conflicts in data) and 3 (inappropriate methods), we used three recently developed approaches (*BEAST, BEST, and MDC) that accommodate discordance amongst gene trees to estimate species trees. Finally, to address point 4 (insufficient data) we included the largest molecular data set and the most dense species sampling effort (188 terminals, 14 loci) of any phylogenetic study of this genus.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF69A3CFFC64A3BD5D7C2DFFB3CFDF2" blockId="10.[144,759,198,1902]" lastBlockId="10.[806,1422,197,1902]" pageId="10" pageNumber="179">
After considering all of these likely causes of poor phylogenetic reconstruction and still not resolving some polytomies, we performed statistical tests of diversification hypotheses within the 
<taxonomicName id="4C49E1BFFFC64A3BD486C33AFDFEF8AF" box="[505,618,1851,1872]" class="Reptilia" family="Liolaemidae" genus="Liolaemus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="10" pageNumber="179" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="montanus">
<emphasis id="B93D462EFFC64A3BD486C33AFDFEF8AF" box="[505,618,1851,1872]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="179">montanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
section. We tested two models with one and two hard polytomies (with estimated divergence times of 10.14 and 5.48 Mya, respectively) in the broader context of five models based on different published topologies and a sixth alternative based on our *BEAST results (Fig. 1). We found some support for all these models (
<figureCitation id="137286B9FFC64A3BD1A8C541FA8EFEA9" box="[1239,1306,320,342]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="7.[164,243,1526,1545]" captionTargetBox="[164,1445,194,1496]" captionTargetId="figure-0@7.[164,1445,194,1496]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figure 3. Empirical Eulaemus phylogenetic hypotheses. Phylogenetic results using the full matrix of 188 taxa (A, B) and a reduced set of 40 taxa chosen to subsample the largest clades (C to F). A, topology recovered from the concatenated matrix; B, species tree recovered by the minimizing deep coalescence (MDC) approach; C, *BEAST results of partial matrix with representatives of largest clades; values on branches are estimated divergences times (upper) and posterior probability values estimated (lower) or separated by a slash; bold branches represent nodal support&gt; 0.90; D, BEST result; E, MDC result of partial matrix; and F, partial concatenated matrix. In (A), (D), and (F) nodes with support &lt;0.90 were collapsed. The calibration point for estimation of divergence times is shown with a white circle in the node corresponding to the divergence of the Eulaemus and Liolaemus clades." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5337488" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5337488/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="179">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
), but the strongest support favoured the ‘two hard polytomies’ model (nine loci), followed by the ‘one hard polytomy’ model (eight loci). The models based on the 
<bibRefCitation id="EFD8E7CDFFC64A3BD048C59DFC3DFE2F" author="Schulte JA II &amp; Macey JR &amp; Espinoza RE &amp; Larson A" pageId="10" pageNumber="179" pagination="75 - 102" refId="ref11644" refString="Schulte JA II, Macey JR, Espinoza RE, Larson A. 2000. Phylogenetic relationships in the iguanid lizard genus Liolaemus: multiple origins of viviparous reproduction and evidence for recurring Andean vicariance and dispersal. Biological Journal of the Linnean Society 69: 75 - 102." type="journal article" year="2000">
Schulte 
<emphasis id="B93D462EFFC64A3BD659C5BAFCC2FE30" box="[806,854,442,464]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="179">et al</emphasis>
. (2000)
</bibRefCitation>
hypothesis and our *BEAST analysis were supported by seven loci, and the 
<bibRefCitation id="EFD8E7CDFFC64A3BD1E0C5D8FAF3FE10" author="Avila LJ &amp; Morando M &amp; Sites JW Jr." box="[1183,1383,473,495]" pageId="10" pageNumber="179" pagination="241 - 275" refId="ref9720" refString="Avila LJ, Morando M, Sites JW Jr. 2006. Congeneric phylogeography: hypothesizing species limits and evolutionary processes in Patagonian lizards of the Liolaemus boulengeri group (Squamata: Liolaemini). Biological Journal of the Linnean Society 89: 241 - 275." type="journal article" year="2006">
Avila 
<emphasis id="B93D462EFFC64A3BD19EC5DBFA86FE11" box="[1249,1298,473,495]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="179">et al</emphasis>
. (2006)
</bibRefCitation>
topology was supported by six loci.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF69A3CFFC64A3BD640C617FB2AFCC0" blockId="10.[806,1422,197,1902]" pageId="10" pageNumber="179">
Hard polytomies are recognized by very short internodes for which by chance every descendent lineage has the same probability of receiving one allele (
<bibRefCitation id="EFD8E7CDFFC64A3BD652C673FBEEFD77" author="McCracken KG &amp; Sorenson MD" box="[813,1146,626,648]" pageId="10" pageNumber="179" pagination="35 - 55" refId="ref11254" refString="McCracken KG, Sorenson MD. 2005. Is homoplasy or lineage sorting the source of incongruent mtDNA and nuclear gene trees in the stiff-tailed ducks (Nomonyx - Oxyura)? Systematic Biology 54: 35 - 55." type="journal article" year="2005">McCracken &amp; Sorenson, 2005</bibRefCitation>
). This implies that when multiple loci are analysed we would expect to find support for different gene tree topologies owing to a stochastic pattern of shared allele sorting amongst lineages. As the length of the internode increases, an increasing proportion of gene trees should become congruent with the species history.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF69A3CFFC64A3BD640C749FC5EFA7A" blockId="10.[806,1422,197,1902]" pageId="10" pageNumber="179">
Our tests suggest that two hard polytomies are the most plausible explanation for the history of this clade amongst the eight models evaluated. However, the difference between two and one hard polytomy models is only one locus, and we note that differences probably reflect the uncertainty of a real statistical difference between these results. As the ‘two hard polytomies’ hypothesis is the most strongly supported, and because we recovered the 
<taxonomicName id="4C49E1BFFFC64A3BD063C03CFA19FBAD" box="[1308,1421,1085,1106]" class="Reptilia" family="Liolaemidae" genus="Liolaemus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="10" pageNumber="179" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="melanops">
<emphasis id="B93D462EFFC64A3BD063C03CFA19FBAD" box="[1308,1421,1085,1106]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="179">melanops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
series as monophyletic in most phylogenetic analyses (
<figureCitation id="137286B9FFC64A3BD651C07BFC65FB70" box="[814,1009,1146,1168]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="7.[164,243,1526,1545]" captionTargetBox="[164,1445,194,1496]" captionTargetId="figure-0@7.[164,1445,194,1496]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figure 3. Empirical Eulaemus phylogenetic hypotheses. Phylogenetic results using the full matrix of 188 taxa (A, B) and a reduced set of 40 taxa chosen to subsample the largest clades (C to F). A, topology recovered from the concatenated matrix; B, species tree recovered by the minimizing deep coalescence (MDC) approach; C, *BEAST results of partial matrix with representatives of largest clades; values on branches are estimated divergences times (upper) and posterior probability values estimated (lower) or separated by a slash; bold branches represent nodal support&gt; 0.90; D, BEST result; E, MDC result of partial matrix; and F, partial concatenated matrix. In (A), (D), and (F) nodes with support &lt;0.90 were collapsed. The calibration point for estimation of divergence times is shown with a white circle in the node corresponding to the divergence of the Eulaemus and Liolaemus clades." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5337488" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5337488/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="179">Fig. 3A, C, D, F</figureCitation>
) with a longer average speciation time (7.91–5.48 = 2.33 Mya interval), we accept this model as the best working hypothesis. If rapid simultaneous radiations of lineages is the true history for this clade, then the incongruence amongst previously published studies is expected; all of these studies found some well-supported topological differences amongst the main clades regardless of the method or data set used.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF69A3CFFC64A3AD640C18CFE60FF04" blockId="10.[806,1422,197,1902]" lastBlockId="11.[164,778,198,251]" lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="180" pageId="10" pageNumber="179">
Phylogenetic methods are designed to locate dichotomies in trees, and until recently none was appropriate to search for a shared MRCA amongst three or more lineages. Traditional concatenated analyses also tend to inflate nodal support for dichotomies that may not be real (
<bibRefCitation id="EFD8E7CDFFC64A3BD6F5C227FB6DF9C3" author="Belfiore NM &amp; Liang L &amp; Moritz C" box="[906,1273,1574,1596]" pageId="10" pageNumber="179" pagination="294 - 310" refId="ref9826" refString="Belfiore NM, Liang L, Moritz C. 2008. Multilocus phylogenetics of a rapid radiation in the genus Thomomys (Rodentia: Geomyidae). Systematic Biology 57: 294 - 310." type="journal article" year="2008">Belfiore, Liang &amp; Moritz, 2008</bibRefCitation>
), but modelbased approaches now provide new analytical possibilities (
<bibRefCitation id="EFD8E7CDFFC64A3BD61BC262FB9CF986" author="Knowles LL" box="[868,1032,1635,1657]" pageId="10" pageNumber="179" pagination="593 - 612" refId="ref10786" refString="Knowles LL. 2009. Statistical phylogeography. Annual Review of Ecology, Evolution, and Systematics 40: 593 - 612." type="journal article" year="2009">Knowles, 2009</bibRefCitation>
), and we designed such a test here to shed light on the evolutionary history of the 
<taxonomicName id="4C49E1BFFFC64A3BD05EC283FA19F968" authorityName="Girard" authorityYear="1857" box="[1313,1421,1666,1687]" class="Reptilia" family="Tropiduridae" genus="Eulaemus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="10" pageNumber="179" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93D462EFFC64A3BD05EC283FA19F968" box="[1313,1421,1666,1687]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="179">Eulaemus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
clade. Our results suggest that the most plausible species tree for this clade includes two hard polytomies amongst lineages, and describes two events of rapid radiation of lineages in 
<taxonomicName id="4C49E1BFFFC64A3BD14DC2FDFB36F8EE" authorityName="Girard" authorityYear="1857" box="[1074,1186,1788,1809]" class="Reptilia" family="Tropiduridae" genus="Eulaemus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="10" pageNumber="179" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93D462EFFC64A3BD14DC2FDFB36F8EE" box="[1074,1186,1788,1809]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="179">Eulaemus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
history. If true, then we predict that neither the inclusion of species not sampled here, nor the increase in the number of informative loci, will resolve these polytomies (
<bibRefCitation id="EFD8E7CDFFC64A3AD046C359FE60FF23" author="Delsuc F &amp; Brinkmann H &amp; Philippe H" lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="180" pageId="10" pageNumber="179" pagination="361 - 375" refId="ref10253" refString="Delsuc F, Brinkmann H, Philippe H. 2005. Phylogenomics and the reconstruction of the tree of life. Nature 6: 361 - 375." type="journal article" year="2005">Delsuc, Brinkmann &amp; Philippe, 2005</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFD8E7CDFFC74A3AD77DC4C7FC92FF23" author="Rokas A &amp; Carroll SB" box="[514,774,198,220]" pageId="11" pageNumber="180" pagination="1899 - 1904" refId="ref11561" refString="Rokas A, Carroll SB. 2006. Bushes in the Tree of Life. PLoS Biology 4: 1899 - 1904." type="journal article" year="2006">Rokas &amp; Carroll, 2006</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFD8E7CDFFC74A3AD5DBC4E5FE7CFF04" author="Whitfield JB &amp; Lockhart PJ" box="[164,488,228,251]" pageId="11" pageNumber="180" pagination="258 - 265" refId="ref12162" refString="Whitfield JB, Lockhart PJ. 2007. Deciphering ancient rapid radiations. Trends in Ecology &amp; Evolution 22: 258 - 265." type="journal article" year="2007">Whitfield &amp; Lockhart, 2007</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
